IDENTIFY the peritoneum lining the pelvic cavity.

NOTICE that it covers the superior surface of the urinary bladder, reflects off the urinary bladder to cover most of the uterus, and then reflects off the uterus to cover the anterolateral surface of the rectum.
This creates a vesicouterine pouch between the urinary bladder and the uterus, and a rectouterine pouch (of Douglas) between the rectum and the uterus.

The peritoneum clothes the lateral wall of the pelvis, and in passing over the uterine tubes, forms a poncho-like structure, the broad ligament that contains the uterine blood vessels, nerves and lymphatics.
It also contains the round ligament of the uterus, the remnant of the fetal gubernaculum (see exercise 3.2), which extends to the deep inguinal ring to enter the inguinal canal.
